Q10: The only academic misconduct I have witnessed is peers helping peers with labs and problem sets. I don't think this should be considered academic misconduct at all. And if the course really is about learning the content then why is something that helps students learn considered misconduct? All of those cases of acamic misconduct would not exist if they weren't considered academic misconduct at all and were instead recognized as helpful learning tools.

I think the problem is that it is too easy to cheat and too hard to get caught. I'm not sure how the detection system can be improved but maybe you can have a couple different versions of homework/exams to make cheating harder.

Eliminating academic misconduct for labs, problem sets and lecture starters is probably not possible.  Attention should be focused on better preventing academic misconduct during exams.  Access to a live internet connection during exams provides the opportunity for racket starter files to be sent/received.
